summary: From 2011, the onset of the Mendenhall GLOF, to 2022, the annual floods were highly variable, ranging from small events that went largely unnoticed to larger events that caused nuisance flooding of roads and a USFS campground and caused only minor property damage. On August 5, 2023, an unprecedented GLOF was released from Suicide Basin causing the Mendenhall River to rise rapidly to approximately 15 feet. This event resulted in widespread erosion along the river corridor in the Mendenhall Valley which swept a home into the river and damaged several other properties that were later condemned (Canny, 2024). Just one year later, on August 6, 2024, another GLOF triggered an even more extreme flood event, with the river cresting at a record-setting 16 feet. This flood resulted in widespread inundation within the Mendenhall Valley, affecting nearly 300 properties and prompting emergency evacuations that extended into the early morning hours (Zerkel, 2024; Travers, 2024).
